{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.53,0.08,0.19,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4356"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"331"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43876"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents with a one month history of episodes of dizziness and feeling faint, associated with some epigastric discomfort. The symptoms seem to be worse after a meal. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, gastric bypass surgery three months ago, and a knee arthroplasty. He has recently been started on verapamil for angina. Physical examination is unremarkable apart from a BMI of 29.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Upper abdominal ultrasound","Post prandial blood sugar","Serum lipase","Endoscopy","CT chest and abdomen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHis symptoms fit well for dumping syndrome. This term is used to describe the early and uncoordinated emptying of food from the stomach into the small bowel. There are two components to dumping. An early phase, occurring some 15 minutes after a meal when the patient experiences vasomotor symptoms of dizziness, light-headedness and nausea. These symptoms reflect a relative hypovolaemia, brought on by fluid shifts secondary to the sudden delivery of highly osmotic materials into the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe late phase of dumping may occur an hour or later after a meal and the symptoms are predominantly a reflection of a reactive hypoglycaemia that may occur after a sudden release of insulin (and over-compensation) to handle a large amount of high carbohydrate suddenly appearing in the small bowel. This is why \u003Cstrong\u003Epost prandial blood sugar\u003C/strong\u003E levels is the most appropriate investigation for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lipase \u003C/strong\u003Eis used to rule out pancreatitis. Whilst it is appropriate to keep this as a possible diagnosis, it is unlikely that this patient has pancreatitis, given the chronicity of the symptoms and their relationship to meals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper abdominal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest and abdomen \u003C/strong\u003Eare inappropriate as these investigation do not have a place in the investigation for dumping syndrome. These imaging investigations would confirm the previous gastric bypass surgery, but would not reveal causes for hypoglycaemic symptoms that the patient is experiencing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eis quite an invasive procedure and in this case would not be the first line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDumping used to be a well recognised sequela of the various procedures (gastric resection, vagotomy) that were performed in the treatment of chronic duodenal ulcer disease. Whilst the aim of these procedures was to reduce acid secretion, all too often they were accompanied by side-effects worse than the symptoms of the original disease. In the era of bariatric surgery, the symptoms of dumping are being seen more frequently as a side-effect of gastric bypass, where food can rapidly pass in an undigested state into the small bowel. Some 85% of patients undergoing a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass will experience some form of dumping - reinforcing the need for them to adhere to an appropriate diet.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The dumping syndrome is a relatively common consequence of gastric bypass surgery and can usually be managed by dietary advice.","Postprandial blood sugar testing is crucial in diagnosing reactive hypoglycaemia associated with dumping syndrome."],"references":["Berg P, McCallum R. Dumping Syndrome: A Review of the Current Concepts of Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Dig Dis Sci. 2016 Jan;61(1):11-8. doi: 10.1007/s10620-015-3839-x. Epub 2015 Sep 22. PMID: 26396002. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26396002/","Scarpellini E, Arts J, Karamanolis G, Laurenius A, Siquini W, Suzuki H, Ukleja A, Van Beek A, Vanuytsel T, Bor S, Ceppa E, Di Lorenzo C, Emous M, Hammer H, Hellstr\u00f6m P, Laville M, Lundell L, Masclee A, Ritz P, Tack J. International consensus on the diagnosis and management of dumping syndrome. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2020 Aug;16(8):448-466. doi: 10.1038/s41574-020-0357-5. Epub 2020 May 26. PMID: 32457534; PMCID: PMC7351708. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32457534/","Hui C, Bauza GJ. Dumping Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470542/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:39:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:41:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4356"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co